xxbos xxmaj is there a language or design pattern that allows the * removal * of object behavior or properties in a class hierarchy ? < p > a well - know xxunk of traditional class xxunk is that they are bad when it comes to model the real world . xxmaj as an example , trying to represent animals species with classes . xxmaj there are actually several problems when doing that , but one that i never saw a solution to is when a sub - class " xxunk " a behavior or properties that was defined in a super - class , like a xxunk not being able to fly ( there are probably better examples , but that 's the first one that comes to my mind , having seen " xxmaj xxunk 2 " recently ) . < / p > 
 
  < p > xxmaj on the one hand , you do n't want to define for every property and behavior some flag that specifies if it is at all present , and check it every time before accessing that behavior or property . xxmaj you would just like to say that xxunk can fly , simply and clearly , in the xxmaj xxunk class . xxmaj but then it would be nice if one could define " exceptions " xxunk , without having to use some horrible hacks everywhere . xxmaj this often happens when a system has been productive for a while . xxmaj you suddenly find an " exception " that does n't fit in the original design at all , and you do n't want to change a large portion of your code to accommodate it . < / p > 
 
  < p > xxmaj so , is there some language or design patterns that can cleanly handle this problem , without requiring major changes to the " super - class " , and all the code that uses it ? xxmaj even if a solution only handle a specific case , several solutions might together form a complete strategy . < / p > 
 
  < p>[edit ] xxmaj forgot about the xxmaj xxunk xxmaj substitution xxmaj principle . xxmaj that is why you ca n't do it . xxmaj assuming you define " xxunk / interfaces " for all major " feature groups " , you can xxunk implement xxunk in different branches of the hierarchy , like the xxmaj xxunk trait could be implemented by xxmaj xxunk , and some special kind of xxunk and xxunk . < / p > 
 
  < p > xxmaj so my question could amount to " xxmaj how could i un - implement a trait ? " xxmaj if your super - class is a xxmaj java xxmaj serializable , you have to be one too , even if there is no way for you to serialize your state , for example if you contained a " xxmaj socket " . < / p > 
 
  < p > xxmaj so one way to do it is to always define all your xxunk in pair from the start : xxmaj xxunk and xxunk ( which would throw xxunk , if not checked against ) . xxmaj the xxmaj not - trait would not define any new interface , and could be simply checked for . xxmaj sounds like a " cheap " solution , in particular if used from the start . < / p >
